data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, etc.) and `SaveChanges()` will throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

The opt-in you configured in .NET 10:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(...).AllowSynchronousIO();
```

…no longer exists. The API has been removed.

## Fix: Convert to Async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- Every query/save against Cosmos must be `async` now — there is no workaround.
- `Add()` is still synchronous (it's in-memory tracking), only the terminal operators and `SaveChanges` need the async versions.
- You'll need to propagate `async/await` up through your call stack (controllers, services, etc.).
